article.headline: Wichita State 72, George Mason 66
article.story: FAIRFAX, Va. (AP) -- Wichita State spoiled George Mason's Final Four banner party and avenged a loss in the NCAA tournament, beating the Patriots 72-66 before the largest crowd for a basketball game in Patriot Center history. Sean Ogirri scored all of his 19 points in the second half, Ryan Martin scored a career-high 16, and Kyle Wilson also had 16 for the Shockers (3-0), who closed a tight game with a 17-12 run as they beat the Patriots for the first time in three tries in 2006. John Vaughan scored 21, and Folarin Campbell added 16 for the Patriots (1-1), who were looking for their first 2-0 start since 1995. The game was supposed to be an afternoon of all-out celebration at the Patriots' home opener, one last chance for George Mason to celebrate its improbable Final Four run eight months ago. The crowd of 9,804 marked only the fourth sellout ever at the arena and the first in more than five years. It was also the first sellout against an opponent other than in-state rival James Madison. Twenty minutes before tip-off, the crowd cheered long and hard as the "George Mason 2006 NCAA Final Four Indianapolis" banner was slowly raised in the corner of the arena. Players then ran to high-five the fans in the front row of the student section, and the band kicked off another rendition of "Livin' on a Prayer," the team's unofficial fight song during its remarkable postseason. There were other scenes unthinkable at previous George Mason home openers. Long lines of traffic backed well onto the main highway, and tailgaters were scattered throughout the lots. No one was cheered more than coach Jim Larranaga, who signed a long-term contract extension during the offseason. Once the game was underway, it looked much like a repeat of the teams' meetings in February (ESPN "Bracket Buster") and March (NCAA tournament round of 16) -- a tense, competitive tussle between evenly matched mid-majors. George Mason won both games last season, but the Patriots returned only two starters while the Shockers returned four. The Patriots led 33-27 at halftime, but the Shockers tied it with a 6-0 run to start the second half. Wichita State led 55-54 with 6:49 remaining when Ogirri made a 3-pointer. He added seven more points down the stretch to help put the game away.
